## 3. THE NESTED STACK PROTOCOL (NSP) — Parallel Architecture

**NSP** is a recursive objection-elimination architecture that operates in parallel to CCAI. It was developed as a stress-test validation architecture to prove that deterministic output is not unique to a single topology.

### 3.1 NSP Topology

| Feature | CCAI | NSP |
|---------|------|-----|
| **Structure** | Linear A-G sequence with silo parallelism | Recursive tree: each limitation spawns an autonomous child stack |
| **Scaling** | Fractal (down to micro, up to macro) | Nested (parent limitation → child stack → grandchild stack) |
| **Supervision** | Gem G Master Supervisor | Master Supervisor per level, with upward feed to parent |
| **Output Gate** | 300% threshold | 300% threshold at **every** branch level |
| **Execution** | Parallel silos | Parallel child stacks |

### 3.2 The Recursive Tree

When NSP encounters a limitation:
1. The limitation becomes the **root** of a child stack.
2. The child stack has its own silos, its own 300% gate, and its own Master Supervisor.
3. Multiple child stacks run in parallel.
4. Solutions feed **upward** to dissolve the parent limitation.
5. The tree is **complete** when every branch at every level terminates in a 300% deterministic output.

**Significance:** NSP proves that deterministic intelligence is not a single implementation but a **class of architectures**. This strengthens the prior-art claim by demonstrating that the underlying principle — deterministic generative elimination of hallucination — is reproducible across distinct topologies.

